s of the Dutch East Indies began to translate literature from most places in the world. Siegel discovers in that moment a force within communication more important than the specific messages it conveyed. The subsequent containment of this linguistic force he calls the "fetish of modernity," which, like other fetishes, was thought to be able to compel events. Here, the event is the recognition of the bearer of the fetish as a person of the modern world. The taming of this force in Indonesian nationalism and the continuation of its wild form in the revolution are the major subjects of the book. Its material is literature from Indonesian and Dutch as well as first-person accounts of the revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aIndonesian languagexHistory. 0aLanguage and culturezIndonesia. 0aLiterature and revolutions. 0aLiterature and societyzIndonesia. 0aNationalismzIndonesiaxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aBintang Hindia.  aBook of Frauds.  aChambert-Loir.  aChinese.  aChristianity.  aCinto.  aDutchman.  aGroneman.  aIndonesian archipelago.  aMelayu language.  aMuhammad Bakir.  aSelompret Melayoe.  aSitti Saniah.  aStudent Hidjau.  aTionghwa.  aachievement.  aadmonitions.  aambiguous.  aannouncements.  aarchipelago.  aberdandan.  ablackmailer.  acamat.  acharacteristics.  aconservative.  aektremists.  agila hormat.  aimaginary.  aimaginative.  aincomprehensible.  aliterature.  amata doewitan.  amiscommunications.  anarcissism.  anationalism.  anet moeder.  anjai.  aprijaji.  arakyat.  areal mother.  arecognition.  arevolution.  arudimentary literacy.  asatisfactorily.  asocial revolution.  asociological.  asympathetic.  ateukeunong.  atransmission.  atuan.  avergctdering.